description.text:
This is an 47mm omniwheel I designed for a project I'm working on. It is designed to be used with a servo horn I designed. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1525078. The servo horn mating diameter is 20mm.

One complete omni wheel includes
1x Omniwheel v2 top.stl
1x Omniwheel v2 bottom.stl
8x Omniwheel v2 roller.stl

Printer:

Maker Select V2

Rafts:

No

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20

Notes:

Processed by simplify 3d.

Main Body
PLA printed at 190C on 60C heated bed.
I used the desnse support layer setting in simplify 3d to add 4 layers of 70% support density with farily decent success to get a cleaner face on where the serve horn sits in omniwheel v2 top.stl.

Rollers:
PETG printed at 245C on 80C heated bed. I've also printed these in PLA at 190C on a 60C bed. With the same kind of post processing described below. But I think the PETG takes the sanding better.

I've sanded the rollers by drilling partially into the 1/16" in bit then running it over sand paper. Once sanded i finish drilling out the rollers with 1/16" bit.

I use a 1.5mm x 15.8mm pin as an axle for the rollers.
http://www.amazon.com/uxcell-Stainless-15-8mm-Fasten-Elements/dp/B008IDOK1G?ie=UTF8&psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_search_detailpage

The M2 nuts are friction fit in the main body. I use my Panavise to put them in.
http://www.amazon.com/Silver-Tone-Metal-Screw-Fastener/dp/B00BG8TFR4?ie=UTF8&psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_search_detailpage

M2 x 10mm cap screws are used to fasten the top and bottom and servo horn.
http://www.amazon.com/Steel-Alloy-Knurled-Screw-M2x10/dp/B00O9Y3ATG/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1462464020&sr=8-1&keywords=m2+10mm

I wanted a stand to hold an iPad in a case and most of the ones I found wouldn't work with a case. Therefore, I took the idea I had for an iPod stand (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1541710) and expanded it to work with an iPad. I tried to make it generic enough so that it will work with any tablet.
Originally I was planning it to be easily disassembled for ease of transport in a computer bag, but it doesn't seem to be able to stay together with the weight of an iPad on it, so I redesigned it a little for the two parts to be glued together (although the Sketchup file still has the original parts in it as well as the redesigned part).

I have included the Sketchup file so anybody who wants to can modify/improve it.

The picture included is of the original 3 piece design. I know my gluing leaves something to be desired as well. I am still new to the 3d printing stuff.

description.text:
This is a simpler version of my original design for the LM8UU x-carriage. It is intended to use with an Orca 0.3, but it can possibly also fit an Orca 0.2 (please let me know your experiences!). Version 5 updates:
  • Increased the length of the LM8UU holders
  • Decreased the width of the LM8UU holders
    • Version 4 updates:
  • rounder at the belt holder to use complete print bed
  • other kind of holders which are stiffer
  • room for tiewraps in the holders to keep the bearings in place
  • moved bolt holes a bit so M4 bolts can be used
  • moved the belt clamp 1mm so the belt is 100% (candle ;p) straight
    • Version 3 updates:
  • reinforced bottom plate a bit
  • added more bolt holes so it (could) be attached with 6 bolts
    • Version 2 updates:
  • had to cut off one part of the belt clamp for the motor bolt to fit
  • made the belt clamps a bit wider to fit the belt more easily
  • made the LM8UU holders a bit tighter (now 24.00mm x 16.50mm dia)
  • rounded the edge of the belt holder to make it slide more to the right/left

Version 5 is final, printed & tested. Fits properly. (you will need M3 sunkhead bolts for the inner bolts to fit properly in V2.3 this is fixed in V2.4)
  • Print it (make sure when you remove it from the heated bet while it's hot that you put it down on a flat surface so it cools down without bending)
  • Put in the LM8UU bearings while it's COLD!
  • Remove the parts from the original x-carriage
  • Attach the printed holder with 4 bolts
  • Push the belt inside the belt holder
  • Enjoy printing!

description.text: A tesselating gecko based on the works of M C Escher. There's nine in the file, at what I thought was an appropriate scale. Two layers, cut the "0" layer and etch the um... "Etch" layer. I etched it as vectors with the laser slightly (about 6 or 7 mm) out of focus. This makes the lines nice and wide. Top tip there, defocused etching is brilliant. I've only printed these nine as a test in 1/8'' MDF so far, but they go together nicely. Make an infinite number in different colours and use them to cover your walls. It'll look nice. I promise.

My inspiration for this jewelry set came from a fine jewelry set with a silver pendant and chain. I was struck by the curved arrow shape of the pendant which I incorporated in my design. Instead of cutting out a web of geometric shapes as in the original pendant, I rastered a geometric pattern on the pendant instead. For the earrings, I used the shape of the cutout in the center of the necklace pendant and simply added a cut out at the top to attach to the ear wire. I created the design in Illustrator and printed it using a laser engraver.

The necklace pendant and earrings were laser cut from a 3mm wood board with vector settings: speed 30, power 100, frequency 500 Hz on a 40 watt Epilog Engraver and rastered at 60% speed and 100% power. I coated all of the wooden pieces with 2-3 layers of a protective polyurethane coating. I colored several of the triangles blue with a pen and added another coating of the polyurethane to prevent the color from smudging. I used hemp cord to tie onto the pendant, added a few beads as accents, and finally added a lobster claw clasp. The earrings were linked to the fish hook ear wire with a jump ring as well.

title: Pergo Use CHEAPER 3" Chlorine Tablets in your Spa!

description.text:
Print settings is !VERY! important
Print 6-8% infill !!!! Solid plastic does NOT float!
The lower you can print infill the better
2.0 mm shell/walls as any thinner and it will not be water tight.
^-- at least 5 shells (.4 x 5=2.0mm or .8 x 3 =2.4mm)
I did print with both .4 mm and .8 mm nozzles and both worked fine.
the .4 mm version looks better, the .8 version takes 1/4 the time to print.
PLA only lasts about solid 4 months before you will need another one. Mine is still ok but the did soften and shows bleaching to where you can rub it apart in the inner compartment and the bottom where you drilled the holes.
Recommend PETG.
Even though the water is always 105F or less in a spa. Unless your making cream of brain soup! PLA does get slowly degrade with heated chlorine.

3" pool tablets are much cheaper than the 1" tablets that are sold for spa use.
50 lbs can cost about $143 vs $99-111 for the same weight of 3" tablets and after my tests, the 3" even seem to last longer.

I did a h311 of a lot of work on this floater, Being that a 3" tablet is made for 5000 gallons of water and my Fourwinds hot tub at 94" x 94" is only 550 gallons. Ya it's big a one :p I even had to put a garage door in my basement to get the tub in the house.

Start out with one hole drilled at first. After 2 weeks if you don't get enough chlorine in the water, move for a 2nd hole. Keep the holes in the corners so that the tablet does not block it. I didn't get gunk clogging the holes like I expected. remember the tablets have stabilizer in them. This is added to the water so that the chlorine does not evaporate too fast. Both sun and heated water make chlorine evaporate faster.

Notes: Researching prices for the best deal on tablets lead me to see many complaints of faster dissolving tablets (crap quality) or arrival as power or all broken tablets.
I found the best deal (even including MANY internet searches) as being Sams club as I could walk up open the container and check for broken tablets and take them home right then. Sams sell a 40lb bucket for like $81-84 which adjusted for 50lbs pricing makes it about $111/50 lbs and none of the tablets are broken.

I put one tablet in, went on a 9 day vacation, came back to a sparkling clean hottub with still 15-20mm of tablet still left!!! This thing works better than I designed for. Over time I see that I'm getting about 2 1/2 weeks on each tablet with 2 holes drilled.

comments.text:
I sliced a plate loaded with four of these, hit the go button, went to craft services, and came back to the entire LX crew gawking at my work box. I still haven't used one yet. I printed them with one perimeter, 10 percent 45 degree rectilinear infill, with the top and bottom layers concentric.
Out of the four I printed, three are still going strong. The one that's "broken" still works, but it's close to failure. Parts of the infill have cracked loose and you can hear them rattling around inside. They loaned them out today to a couple local hands who didn't have c-wrenches. The overall consensus is that the printed wrenches are pretty good for anything that needs to be hand-tight. Or for breaking loose things that should have been hand-tight.
comments.author: lithiumfun

comments.text: On the plus side, you'll have a broken $.92 wrench instead of a C clamp fused to your lighting positions (I know one place I work has at least 5 that still have to be sawn off). where did that one wrench fail? I may be able to design it a little sturdier without having to use so much fill.
comments.author: Chaotic-Goodness

comments.text: I printed 2 more today, with 3 perimeters and %50 infill. Slicer says it's 21g, or $.63 worth of filament, each. The first run weighed 12.5g each. These turned out considerably sturdier. The last batch is still getting used, I'm assuming, as no one has cussed me out or thrown one at me. The one that cracked hasn't had any further issues. You can hold it up to a light and see where the infill cracked, it's inside the body of the wrench, slightly beneath and on the wrench-head side of the 5/16 square pipe bolt hole. So far, the only adjustment I've made was to hog out the hole in the handle so I could get a 1/4 inch carabiner in it.

description.text:
A simple ball-maze doesn't meet the requirement of a real puzzle as the eye can simply follow the path and the actual challenge is the plain motoric difficulty. Not so this concept of a double sided maze. The ball has to change the sides two times.

I used a 3 mm steel ball from bike wheel hub.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more designs.
I created a circular grid using Solid Edge 2D and then Illustrator to mark the correct way in green the dead ends in red till all the elements were filled.

title: Tunable Tolerance Tetrahedron Twist Timewasting Toy

description.text:
This tunable tolerance tetrahedron twist timewasting toy thing was inspired by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:186372 . The problem with that thing was that it was just an STL file, with no means for adjusting the "fit" tolerance or scaling. So, one of the students in my lab, Zachary Snyder, spent valuable should-have-been-studying-for-final-exams time on deriving his own formula for it in OpenSCAD... and then I spent too much time trying to print it with various parameters and tweaking the design. Oh yeah, it also can take a shockingly long time to solve the puzzle... especially shocking given that it's just two pieces!

The 20160630 version has a few minor, but significant improvements. The original version uses a turn of 1.0, which makes the parts not fit with those from the new design unless tenth_turns is set to 10 rather than the new default value of 12.

Printer Brand:

MakerGear

Printer:

M2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

not critical

Infill:

some

Notes:

Can print assembled (intertwined) without supports or as separate parts with/without supports; good to use a brim if printing parts separately. Tests ranging in size from 20 to 75mm on a side were printed on two MakerGear M2 (at up to 150mm/s) and a Wanhao I3 (at up to 60mm/s) using PLA with extrusion heights of 0.1mm to 0.25mm. The parts vary dramatically in thickness, so be warned that thin sections are much more fragile than the thicker sections, and extra shells or infill may be needed to improve durability when idiots try to solve the puzzle by forcing pieces together....

The 20160630 version defaults to having slightly thicker thin sections, which help strength. Higher dimensional accuracy prints have been made printing the two parts separately using Slic3r-produced 10% 3D hexagonal fill and supports with 2 layers of shell. You can print two copies of tttttt20160630noUK1.stl to have no UK logo or one copy each of tttttt20160630u.stl and tttttt20160630k.stl for the version with the UK logo.

Printing Intertwined

Believe it or not, this thing can actually print assembled without supports! The 75mm/side pink and blue ones were printed on two different MakerGear M2, blue with 1mm gap and pink with 0.75mm gap, then taken apart and reassembled intermixed. Although both were successful as print assembled without supports, both did require some careful prying with a knife edge to break the minor welds caused by sag during printing. Using very thin walls, 2mm or less, actually helps when printing intertwined.

Printing Separately

Alternatively, you can get a nicer print by using a slicer to separate the two pieces and then print them with support to the bed and a brim to keep them stable. The second STL file was created using Cura for precisely that transformation (Cura's "Lay Flat" command is also helpful if you want to rotate one of the tetrahedrons, as I did), and pieces printed from that file on a MakerGear M2 (at 0.25mm) and Wanhao I3 (at 0.1mm) fit together effortlessly -- that's how the blue (M2, 0.25mm) and natural (I3, 0.1mm) examples in the photo were made.

Printing the 20160630 one-part-at-a-time STLs produces remarkably clean and accurate prints. In fact, the only cleaning needed is snapping-off the support. I didn't even use a file!

Customizer Parameters Are In Microns

The Customizer still doesn't understand decimal input, so all the parameters to this design are given in integer microns -- 1/1000 mm units. For example, a good value for the gap is between about 0.25mm and 1mm, which would be obtained by setting Micron Gap between 250 and 1000 in the Customizer.

Solving The Puzzle

If you print this as separate parts, you will undoubtedly be tempted at some point to just force the pieces together. DO NOT FORCE THEM. With a 1mm gap, the pieces are actually a DISTURBINGLY LOOSE FIT -- if you are putting them together the right way. Thing 186372 didn't leave a gap, so they talk about needing to sand the parts, but no sanding is required if you leave a gap (although you'll still want to file-off any remaining brim, support material, or hanging threads/stray blobs).

What is the right way to put the two pieces together? Well, the version with the UK logo makes it a little easier to visualize, but the truth is that the simple spiral slicing doesn't line-up with the tetrahedron in one of the planes you expect it to. Once you find the right plane, it is a trivial matter of literally screwing the two parts together.

description.text:
